## 2. Project purpose

This repository is upstream PuTTY plus a **native macOS GUI** (`macos/`) using **Swift / AppKit**, integrated via **CMake**. Treat the portable C core as production networking/crypto/terminal code; treat `macos/` as a third front-end platform alongside `windows/` and `unix/`.

Optimize for:

- Correctness and security at the C / bridge boundary
- Reuse of portable core (`Seat` / `TermWin` / `LogPolicy` in `putty.h`)
- Reviewable, minimal diffs (especially outside `macos/`)
- Main-thread safety for AppKit and PuTTY C calls
- Maintainable C↔Swift bridge ownership
- Universal 2 release artifacts when shipping GUI apps

---

## 3. Core architectural principles

- Prefer the **`macos/` platform** (`PUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON`) for the native GUI — do **not** revive GTK-on-Quartz (`OSX_GTK`, `unix/osxlaunch.c`, bundler paths).
- Keep the portable C core and vtable boundaries intact; extend via `macos/platform/`, `macos/bridge/`, and Swift UI — do not fork SSH/terminal logic into Swift.
- Swift consumes a **stable C bridge** (`macos/bridge/putty-bridge.h`, `PuttyBridge` module). Prefer C wrappers over exposing internal struct layouts or direct vtable manipulation from Swift.
- **All PuTTY C / bridge calls on the main thread** (matches AppKit). UI mutations stay on the main thread (`DispatchQueue.main.async` from C callbacks).
- CLI tools may continue via the `unix/` platform on Darwin unless explicitly moved; do not flip `PUTTY_MACOS_GUI` inside an existing build tree — use separate build dirs.
- Do not hard-code secrets, machine-specific paths, or environment assumptions into committed code.

---

## 4. Tooling expectations

Assume / prefer:

- **CMake ≥ 3.28**, **Ninja** (dev / host-arch), **Xcode generator** (Universal 2)
- **Xcode 16+**, **Swift 6**, macOS **15+** deployment target
- `./macos/build.sh` for configure/build/open/verify/test (Bash 5.x)
- SwiftLint / SwiftFormat (`macos/.swiftlint.yml`, `macos/.swiftformat`)
- clang-tidy / clang analyze scoped to `macos/` only (`make tidy-c`, `make analyze-c`)
- CTest labels via `./macos/build.sh test` / `make test` (see `macos/TESTING.md`)

Do not reformat or tidy upstream root / `unix/` / `windows/` C with macos-only style tools unless the user explicitly asks.

---

## 5. Repository shape (macOS GUI)

```text
macos/
├── README.md, TESTING.md, PARITY.md, AGENT.md, …
├── build.sh
├── platform/          # Darwin C platform (from unix/, no GTK)
├── bridge/            # putty-bridge.h + C session/conf/eventloop API
├── PuttyMacUI/        # Shared Swift/AppKit UI
├── PuTTY/, pterm/, puttygen/
├── tests/             # XCTest + smoke helpers
└── Resources/
```

Platform selection (see `cmake/setup.cmake` / plan):

- Windows → `windows/`
- Darwin + `PUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON` → `macos/`
- otherwise → `unix/`

Respect existing structure unless clearly harmful or the user requests restructuring. Prefer the smallest coherent change; avoid broad “fix everything” refactors.

---

## 6. Build and run rules

Prefer the helper script from the repo root:

```bash
./macos/build.sh check
./macos/build.sh --dev                 # Debug, host arch
./macos/build.sh open --dev
./macos/build.sh test --dev
./macos/build.sh --universal           # Universal 2 (Xcode generator)
./macos/build.sh verify --universal
```

Guidance:

- Use separate build directories for GUI vs CLI and for sanitizer/coverage trees.
- Universal 2 requires the Xcode generator; Ninja + `PUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=ON` is host-arch only (with warning).
- Do not enable sanitizers/coverage on Universal release / notarized builds; do not combine sanitizers with coverage in one tree.
- A successful local host-arch run does not override Universal / signing / notarization requirements for release artifacts.

---

## 7. Layering rules

| Layer | Location | Agents should |
|-------|----------|---------------|
| Portable core | `terminal/`, `ssh/`, `crypto/`, … | Change only when the bug/feature is truly cross-platform; keep diffs minimal |
| Win32 / GTK reference | `windows/`, `unix/window.c` | Read for parity; do not copy Win32/GTK UI code into Swift |
| macOS C platform | `macos/platform/` | Adapt unix shims; no GTK |
| C bridge | `macos/bridge/` | Opaque handles, explicit ownership, main-thread asserts |
| Swift UI | `macos/PuttyMacUI/`, app targets | AppKit, not SwiftUI-style bindings for core session UI |

If a change depends on an AppKit, Swift, CMake, or PuTTY API capability, verify that capability before building logic around it.

---

## 8. Safety and change-control rules

- Default to safe, reviewable changes.
- Prefer fixing bugs in the owning layer (core vs platform vs bridge vs UI).
- Do not add destructive or security-sensitive behavior without calling it out.
- Call out assumptions that depend on macOS version, sandboxing, Keychain, `$SSH_AUTH_SOCK`, display scale, or arch (arm64 vs x86_64).
- Known parity gaps (X11, GSSAPI, serial, etc.) live in `macos/PARITY.md` — do not silently invent incomplete substitutes without disclosure.
- SSH agent default is system OpenSSH via `$SSH_AUTH_SOCK` (`macos/AGENT.md`); do not assume a Pageant.app exists.

If a change is risky and cannot be made meaningfully safe, say so before implementing it.

---

## 9. Testing expectations

Before considering work complete, prefer this ladder (as applicable):

1. Build the relevant profile (`./macos/build.sh --dev` or existing tree)
2. `make quality` / Swift lint+format lint for Swift changes under `macos/`
3. Targeted CTest labels (`unit`, `crypt`, `perf`, `xctest`, `macos`)
4. Keep the Phase 4 paint-budget / termwin perf gate green for terminal rendering work
5. Sanitizer or thread smokes when touching concurrency / bridge lifetime

Typical commands:

```bash
./macos/build.sh test --dev
make test-perf          # terminal paint budget — do not drop casually
make test-ui
make quality
```

If validation cannot be run, state exactly what was not run and why.

---

## 10. Documentation expectations

When changing behavior, update the relevant docs:

- `MACOS_GUI_PLAN.md` — phase/architecture status when phases change
- `macos/README.md` — build/run instructions
- `macos/TESTING.md`, `PARITY.md`, `AGENT.md`, `HELP.md`, `INTEGRATION.md` as applicable
- Root `README` macOS section when user-facing build steps change

Do not let code drift away from usage instructions.

---

## 11. What agents should avoid

- Do not revive abandoned GTK/macOS or ~2005 Cocoa approaches.
- Do not put session/SSH business logic in Swift that belongs in C core or bridge.
- Do not escape raw pointers from Swift scoped memory APIs (see bridge-and-ui rule).
- Do not assume workstation-only paths are the source of truth for release builds.
- Do not replace bridge/vtable patterns with ad hoc Swift↔C sprawl.
- Do not add broad refactors outside the requested scope.
- Do not rationalize brittle glue as clean native design.
- Do not continue implementing after discovering the approach is fundamentally blocked.

---

## 12. Preferred contribution pattern

1. Identify the owning layer (core / `macos/platform` / bridge / Swift UI / build).
2. Verify required capabilities before building around them.
3. Respect existing structure unless clearly harmful.
4. Make the smallest coherent change.
5. Keep style consistent with the touched tree (`macos/` vs upstream C).
6. Run relevant build/lint/tests.
7. Summarize what changed, why, what was verified, and any remaining assumptions.
8. Offer a conventional commit message for review (do not commit/push unless asked — see `general.mdc`).

---

## 13. Decision heuristics

When in doubt:

- choose the more truthful option
- choose the more feasible option
- choose the option that preserves portable-core boundaries
- choose the more explicit ownership / threading option
- choose the option that keeps UI and PuTTY C on the main thread
- choose the option that passes the relevant gates and is easy to review

If those conflict, prioritize truth and feasibility first.
